The core flow involves: 1) User signs in via Google (storing API tokens in Chrome storage). 2) Sidebar fetches memories via `GET /v1/memories`. 3) On supported AI sites, a content script detects the `Mem0 trigger`, calls `POST /v1/memories/search` to fetch relevant memories, and prepends them to the chat input. 4) User can delete memories directly from the chat interface. 5) New chat messages are sent to Mem0 (`POST /v1/memories`) to update memories for future use. Example API calls:
javascript
// Fetch memories
fetch('/v1/memories', { method: 'GET' })
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(memories => console.log(memories));

// Search memories
fetch('/v1/memories/search', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({ query: 'user preferences' })
});

OpenMemory uses a Chrome Manifest V3 architecture with: 1) `background.js` as the MV3 service worker for toolbar actions and initialization. 2) `popup.html/popup.js` for Google sign-in UI. 3) `sidebar.js` for the injected memory dashboard sidebar. 4) Site-specific integration scripts (e.g., `chatgpt/content.js`, `claude/content.js`) to handle AI-assistant-specific triggers and context injection. The `manifest.json` declares all wiring between these components. Example manifest snippet:

{
  "manifest_version": 3,
  "name": "OpenMemory",
  "version": "1.0",
  "background": { "service_worker": "background.js" },
  "content_scripts": [
    { "js": ["chatgpt/content.js"], "matches": ["*://chatgpt.com/*"] }
  ]
}
